Priya Sharma, a 20-year-old B.Com student from Bhopal, was looking for an affordable laptop ahead of her semester exams. She came across a listing on OLX — a Dell laptop priced at ₹18,000, well below the market rate. The seller, who claimed to be an army officer stationed in Pune, communicated politely and appeared credible. He told Priya that since he was posted away from the city, she would need to pay in advance and the laptop would be couriered to her.
To "confirm the order," the seller sent Priya a QR code via WhatsApp, explaining that scanning it would deduct a small security deposit that would be automatically refunded once the delivery was confirmed. Trusting the seller, Priya scanned the code on her PhonePe app and entered her UPI PIN. Within seconds, ₹18,000 was debited from her account. She immediately called the seller, who apologised for a "system glitch" and asked her to scan a second QR code to process the refund. Believing him, Priya complied — and lost another ₹18,000. The seller's number went unreachable within minutes, the OLX listing vanished, and Priya was left with a total loss of ₹36,000 — nearly her entire semester's savings.
